Yes, 

I need state in checkbox indicator to animate indicator with motion.
States such as checked, intermediate are required in indicator.

```ts 
export const CheckboxIcon = () => {
  const { checked, indeterminate } = useCheckboxRootContext();
  return (
    <motion.svg
      animate={checked || indeterminate ? "checked" : "unchecked"}
      fill="none"
      initial={false}
      stroke="currentColor"
      strokeWidth="4"
      viewBox="0 0 24 24"
      xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
    >
      <motion.path
        d={indeterminate ? "M5 12h14" : "M4.5 12.75l6 6 9-13.5"}
        strokeLinecap="round"
        strokeLinejoin="round"
        variants={tickVariants}
      />
    </motion.svg>
  );
};

```

You can also see this [Animate UI Checkbox](https://github.com/imskyleen/animate-ui/blob/main/apps/www/registry/primitives/base/checkbox/index.tsx)

Similarly it will also be used to render indicator with children as function receiving states.
There can be pattern such as 

``` ts
<Checkbox.Indicator>
  {({ checked }) => {
    return checked ? <SunIcon /> : <MoonIcon />;
  }}
</Checkbox.Indicator>;
```

---
While many of these use cases can technically be achieved by making the Root component controlled, doing so when building custom slots or public components requires re-implementing internal logic.

For example, developers need to manually:

- Manage controlled/uncontrolled state using `useControlledState`
- Create a new context to share that state
- Reconnect the custom slots with that context

However, this logic already exists internally in Base UI. If Base UI exposed the corresponding Root context hooks, developers could reuse the existing state and behavior instead of re-implementing it.

Providing these hooks would make it much easier to build custom compositions and design-system abstractions on top of Base UI while still relying on the library's internal state management.
